ce:section.ce:para:
Here, we proposed a poly(methyl methacrylate) (PMMA) polymer-based matrix to embed the N-GQDs for the LDS layer for CIGS solar cells. The polymer matrix can reduce the luminescent efficiency via quenching. So, the optimization of the synthesis parameters is crucial to attaining maximal efficiency. The synthesis temperature is an important parameter to control the luminescent efficiency. Therefore, a wide range of annealing temperatures (25, 40, 60, and 80 °C) is used for the synthesis of the N-GQDs/PMMA LDS system. To evaluate the LDS system, the performance parameters (short circuit current density (J

                        sc
                     ), open circuit voltage (V

                        oc
                     ), fill factor (FF), and conversion efficiency (η)) of the cell are appraised. Furthermore, the analytical PV cell parameters (photogenerated current density (J

                        ph
                     ), shunt resistance (R

                        sh
                     ), series resistance (R

                        s
                     ), diode ideality factor (n), and reverse saturation current density (J

                        0
                     )) are predicted and examined for the loss analysis.

The values of Rsc and Roc are determined from the slopes at the short circuit and open circuit conditions (Fig. 9
                        a & b). The values of Jsc, Voc, Jm, Vm, Rsc, and Roc are used in eqs. (1)–(5) to predict the PV cell parameters (listed in Table 3
                        ).
